I have analyzed the communication between the website and Google Sheets. The most common reason for failure is the **Google Apps Script deployment settings** or the **script code not parsing the JSON body correctly**.

Because we use `mode: 'no-cors'` to avoid security blocks, the browser sends the data as a "simple request." For this to work, your Google Apps Script **must** be set up to handle the raw post data.

### 1. The Required Google Apps Script Code
Please ensure your Google Apps Script (the one at the URL you provided) contains exactly this logic:

```javascript
function doPost(e) {
  try {
    var contents = JSON.parse(e.postData.contents);
    var sheetName = contents.sheetName || "Sheet1";
    var ss = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet();
    var sheet = ss.getSheetByName(sheetName) || ss.getSheets()[0];

    // Get all keys except 'sheetName' to write to row
    var headers = sheet.getRange(1, 1, 1, sheet.getLastColumn()).getValues()[0];
    var newRow = headers.map(function(header) {
      return contents[header] || "";
    });

    sheet.appendRow(newRow);
    return ContentService.createTextOutput("Success").setMimeType(ContentService.MimeType.TEXT);
  } catch (err) {
    return ContentService.createTextOutput("Error: " + err).setMimeType(ContentService.MimeType.TEXT);
  }
}
```
**Crucial:** When you deploy, you must select **"Execute as: Me"** and **"Who has access: Anyone"**. If you change the script, you **must** create a "New Deployment" and use the **new URL**.

### 2. Frontend Updates
I have standardized all forms to use a high-reliability fetch pattern, enforced the **46px height** constraint strictly, and implemented the **bottom-aligned footer** with **32px padding** as requested.

