Yes, you are absolutely correct. To make the "auto-header creation" work, you need a **Google Apps Script** that is smart enough to read the keys we are sending (like "First Name", "Track") and automatically create columns for them if they don't exist.

Since the script lives in your Google Drive (not in this React codebase), I cannot update it directly. **You must copy and paste the code below into your Google Apps Script editor.**

### 1. Update Your Google Apps Script
Replace your **entire** existing code in the Google Apps Script editor with this Dynamic Script:

```javascript
function doPost(e) {
  var lock = LockService.getScriptLock();
  lock.tryLock(10000);

  try {
    var doc = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet();
    var requestData = JSON.parse(e.postData.contents);
    var sheetName = requestData.sheetName || "Sheet1"; // Default to Sheet1 if not specified
    var sheet = doc.getSheetByName(sheetName);

    // Create sheet if it doesn't exist
    if (!sheet) {
      sheet = doc.insertSheet(sheetName);
    }

    var headers = sheet.getRange(1, 1, 1, sheet.getLastColumn() || 1).getValues()[0];
    var nextRow = sheet.getLastRow() + 1;
    var newRow = [];
    var missingHeaders = [];

    // 1. Map existing headers to incoming data
    // 2. Identify keys in data that don't have headers yet
    for (var key in requestData) {
      if (key === 'sheetName') continue; // Skip internal control param

      var headerIndex = headers.indexOf(key);
      if (headerIndex === -1) {
        missingHeaders.push(key);
      }
    }

    // Add missing headers to the sheet
    if (missingHeaders.length > 0) {
      var startCol = headers.length > 0 && headers[0] !== "" ? headers.length + 1 : 1;
      sheet.getRange(1, startCol, 1, missingHeaders.length).setValues([missingHeaders]);
      // Refresh headers array
      headers = sheet.getRange(1, 1, 1, sheet.getLastColumn()).getValues()[0];
    }

    // Construct the row data based on final headers order
    for (var i = 0; i < headers.length; i++) {
      var header = headers[i];
      var value = requestData[header];

      // Convert arrays (like checkboxes) to string
      if (Array.isArray(value)) {
        newRow.push(value.join(", "));
      } else {
        newRow.push(value || ""); // Push empty string if undefined
      }
    }

    // Append the sorted row
    sheet.getRange(nextRow, 1, 1, newRow.length).setValues([newRow]);

    return ContentService.createTextOutput(JSON.stringify({ "result": "success", "row": nextRow }))
      .setMimeType(ContentService.MimeType.JSON);

  } catch (e) {
    return ContentService.createTextOutput(JSON.stringify({ "result": "error", "error": e.toString() }))
      .setMimeType(ContentService.MimeType.JSON);
  } finally {
    lock.releaseLock();
  }
}
```

### 2. Save & Deploy
1.  Paste the code above.
2.  Click **Save**.
3.  Click **Deploy** > **New Deployment**.
4.  Select type: **Web app**.
5.  Description: `Dynamic V1`.
6.  Execute as: **Me**.
7.  Who has access: **Anyone**.
8.  Click **Deploy** and ensure you copy the **Web App URL**.
9.  **Important:** If the URL changed, you must update the `SCRIPT_URL` constant in your React files again. If you just updated the code inside an existing deployment (via "Manage Deployments" > Edit > New Version), the URL stays the same.

---

### 3. Frontend Update: Admin Logs
I am also updating the **Responses Page** in your app. Since we changed the data keys from `firstName` to `First Name`, the admin view needs to know how to read these new keys so you can verify submissions locally.

